What is a Linear Model?

A linear model describes a relationship between aresponsevariable and one or morepredictorvariables based on a sample.

For continuous variables: assesses whether the mean value of the response variable differs significantly between different values of the explanatory variables

For categorical explanatory variables: assesses whether the mean value of the response variable differs significantly between different levels (or groups) of explanatory variables

In this workshop, well walk through how to fit different types of linear models in R, interpret their results, and evaluate their assumptions using the sparrows.csv dataset.

The dataset includes measurements of sparrows including weight, wing length, tarsus length, head length, age, sex, and observer identity.

spar <- read.csv("../../Data files/sparrows.csv")

Simple Linear Regression

Lets start with a basic linear model to examine how wing length predicts sparrow weight.

ggplot(spar, aes(x = Wing, y = Weight)) +
  geom_point(size = 2, color = "deeppink") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", color = "black") +
  theme_bw()

model1 <- lm(Weight ~ Wing, data = spar)

Assessing Model Fits and Assumptions

Use built-in diagnostic plots to evaluate model assumptions:

par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
plot(model1)

Interpretation: - Top-left (residuals vs fitted): Look for nonlinearity or heteroscedasticity. - Top-right (QQ plot): Assesses normality of residuals. - Bottom-left (scale-location): Another check for homoscedasticity. - Bottom-right (residuals vs leverage): Identifies influential observations.

The first figure is our residual versus fitted value plot. The red line, included by default, is a smooth through the data and can be used to evaluate the linearity assumption. For small data sets, like this one, this line can be deceiving. To eliminate it, we could add add.smooth=FALSE to the plot function.

The other 3 plots all use standardized residuals, which are also typically referred to as studentized residuals.

The Q-Q plot shows quantiles of the standardized residuals versus quantiles of a standard normal distribution. If the normality assumption holds, we would expect to see the residuals largely fall along the dotted line indicating that the quantiles of the residuals (e.g., their 5th percentile, median, and 90th percentile, etc.) line up with the quantiles of the standard normal distribution.

The next plot is the square-root of absolute values of the standardized residuals versus fitted values. Here, we should see constant scatter along the x-axis if the constant variance assumption holds. Taking the absolute value of the residuals effectively reflects the negative residuals above the horizontal line y=0, making it easier to see departures from constant variance in small data sets.

The final plot shows residuals versus leverage, a measure of how far away each observation is in predictor space from the other observations. Observations with high leverage are often, but not always, highly influential points, meaning that deletion of these points leads to large changes in the regression parameters. In each of the panels, interesting and potentially problematic or influential points are indicated by their row number.

Alternatively, we coudl use the check_model function in sjPlot

check_model(model1)

The slope of the regression line is 0.51. This tells us that the average weight of sparrows change by 0.51 grams for each increase of 1 unit (mm) of wing length

More generally: The intercept = the average value of weight when all predictors are set equal to 0 (if our wing length is 0 mm then the weight is -9.13 grams) The slope = predicted change in Y per unit increase in X

Test the hypothesis

Use anova to test the null hypohtesis that the slope = 0

anova(model1)
## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Response: Weight
##            Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value    Pr(>F)    
## Wing        1 1320.2 1320.17  747.39 < 2.2e-16 ***
## Residuals 977 1725.7    1.77                      
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Under the null hypothesis that the slope is equal to 0, the ratio of 747.39 is unlikely (p < 0.001), and the null hypothesis can be rejected. The ANOVA table therefore provides a test to identify whether there is a linear relationship between Y and X.

Use ANOVA to compare a full model (with slope) to a reduced (null) model.

null_model <- lm(Weight ~ 1, data = spar)

The anova function finds the factors that have been removed in the reduced model as compared to the full model, and tests whether those removed factors are different from zero.

##              Sum Sq  Df  F value    Pr(>F)    
## (Intercept)   61.33   1  34.8900 4.815e-09 ***
## Wing         320.60   1 182.3733 < 2.2e-16 ***
## Sex            8.61   1   4.8951   0.02716 *  
## Wing:Sex       9.00   1   5.1201   0.02387 *  
## Residuals   1713.99 975                       
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Note: The first ANOVA shown above is a Type I (sequential) ANOVA, which means each term is tested after accounting for the ones that precede it in the formula. Since the interaction is listed after both main effects, it is tested last, and main effects are tested without adjusting for the interaction.

However, to properly evaluate main effects in the presence of an interaction, we need to use a Type III ANOVA. This tests each term after adjusting for all other terms, including interactions, and is the appropriate choice when interpreting main effects from models with interaction terms. (Type I), which means that main effects are interpreted after accounting for earlier terms in the formula. Since we have an interaction term, we cannot interpret the main effects directly without first checking if the interaction is significant.

To visualize the interaction and understand what it means, we can use an interaction plot:

plot_model(model4, type = "pred", terms = c("Wing", "Sex"))

visreg(model4, "Wing", by = "Sex")

To statistically test whether the slopes differ between groups (i.e., whether the interaction is significant), we use emtrends() from the emmeans package:

# Estimate slope for each sex group and test if slopes differ
slope_tests <- emtrends(model4, ~ Sex, var = "Wing")

# Compare slopes between sexes (test interaction)
pairs(slope_tests)
##  contrast      estimate     SE  df t.ratio p.value
##  Female - Male    0.119 0.0527 975   2.263  0.0239

If the confidence intervals for the difference in slopes do not include zero, we have evidence that the effect of wing length on weight differs by sex.

To assess whether the slope of Wing is significantly different from zero within each Sex group, use the test() function from the emmeans package. This will extract significance tests for each slope estimate:

test(slope_tests)
##  Sex    Wing.trend     SE  df t.ratio p.value
##  Female      0.613 0.0454 975  13.505  <.0001
##  Male        0.494 0.0268 975  18.395  <.0001

This output provides the estimated slopes, standard errors, t-values, and p-values for each group. A p-value < 0.05 indicates that wing length is a significant predictor of weight for that sex.

When we include multiple continuous predictors, its important to determine whether each contributes uniquely to the model. Because we are interested in assessing the effect of each predictor after accounting for the others, we use a Type II ANOVA, which tests each term after adjusting for all others but not after any interactions, as in Type III.

Type II ANOVA is most appropriate when: - There are no interaction terms in the model - Predictors are not orthogonal (i.e., theyre correlated) - We want to understand marginal effects of each variable, controlling for the others

We can visualize the predictions from this model using ggeffects. Here is an example for Wing, but this is easy to modify for the other predictor.

pred <- ggpredict(model5, terms = "Wing [all]")

# Clean plot with confidence ribbon
ggplot(pred, aes(x = x, y = predicted)) +
  geom_ribbon(aes(ymin = conf.low, ymax = conf.high), fill = "grey80", alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_line(color = "black", size = 1.2) +
  geom_point(data = spar, aes(x = Wing, y = Weight), color = "deeppink", alpha = 0.4, size = 2) +
  labs(x = "Wing Length (mm)", y = "Predicted Weight (g)",
       title = "Model-Predicted Weight by Wing Length\n(Controlling for Tarsus and Head Length)") +
  theme_bw(base_size = 14)

Standardizing Predictors

Standardizing (or scaling) predictors puts them on the same scale by subtracting the mean and dividing by the standard deviation. This is useful when predictors are measured in different units or when comparing their relative importance in a regression model. It also helps with numerical stability and interpretation of interaction terms.

spar <- spar %>% mutate(across(c(Wing, Tarsus, Head), list(s = scale)))
model7 <- lm(Weight ~ Wing_s + Tarsus_s + Head_s, data = spar)
summary(model7)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = Weight ~ Wing_s + Tarsus_s + Head_s, data = spar)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -4.0298 -0.6723 -0.0770  0.6045  6.9316 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) 20.22646    0.03734 541.643  < 2e-16 ***
## Wing_s       0.68776    0.04663  14.748  < 2e-16 ***
## Tarsus_s     0.44527    0.05464   8.150 1.11e-15 ***
## Head_s       0.41561    0.05368   7.742 2.45e-14 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 1.168 on 975 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.563,  Adjusted R-squared:  0.5617 
## F-statistic: 418.7 on 3 and 975 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16
car::vif(model7)
##   Wing_s Tarsus_s   Head_s 
## 1.557892 2.138462 2.064661

The summary() output allows us to compare standardized regression coefficients directly, since all predictors are now on the same scale. This can help us evaluate which predictors have relatively stronger effects on the response variable.

We also calculate the Variance Inflation Factor (VIF) to assess multicollinearity. Values above 510 may indicate problematic collinearity between predictors.

Summary

This workshop demonstrated how to: - Fit linear models in R using lm() - Interpret coefficients and model output - Evaluate assumptions - Compare models using ANOVA - Visualize results using ggplot2, ggeffects, and visreg - Apply models with categorical, continuous, and interaction terms - Use standardization to compare effects across predictors

These tools will form the foundation for more advanced modeling techniques later in the course.

Exercises

Exercise #1: One continous variable

We will start with simple linear regression using one continuous predictor. For this exercise use the dataset RIKZ. This is a data set from Zuur et al.(2009) containing abundances of ~ 75 invertebrate species measured on various beaches along the Dutch Coast. The data were originally published in Janssen & Mulder (2004) and Janssen & Mulder (2005).

In this study, the variable NAP measured the height of the sample site compared with average sea level, and indicated the time a site is under water. A site with a low NAP value will spend more time under water than a site with a high NAP value, and sites with high NAP values normally lie further up the beach. The authors wanted to know how species richness varied with NAP.

Richness = species richness (i.e., the number of species counted). NAP = height of the sample site (relative to sea level). Lower values indicate sites closer to or further below sea level, which implies more time spent submerged.

1. 1. Read the data from the file RIKZdat.csv
2. View the first few lines of data to make sure it was read correctly.
3. Create a scatter plot of the data. Choose the response and explanatory variables with care: we want to predict Richness from height of the sample above sea level.
4. Fit a linear model to the data with species richness (Richness) as the response variable and site height (NAP) as the predictor.
5. Add the best-fit line to the scatter plot. Does the relationship appear linear? From the scatter plot, visually check for any serious problems such as outliers or changes in the variance.
6. Using the same fitted model object, obtain the estimates for the coefficients, slope and intercept, standard errors, and 95% confidence intervals for the slope and intercept. What is the R2 value for the model fit? Hint: use tab_model function from the sjPlot package.
7. Test the fit of the model to the data with an ANOVA table. What does this test tell us?
8. Recall the assumptions of linear models. Do the data conform to the assumptions? Are there any potential concerns? Most of the plots will be self-explanatory, except perhaps the last one. Leverage calculates the influence that each data point has on the estimated parameters. For example, if the slope changes a great deal when a point is removed, that point is said to have high leverage. Cooks distance measures the effect of each data point on the predicted values for all the other data points. A value greater than 1 is said to be worrisome. Points with high leverage dont necessarily have high Cooks distance, and vice versa.

Exercise #2: One categorical variable

Our second example fits a linear model with a categorical explanatory variable. The data are from an experiment by Wright and Czeisler (2002. Science 297: 571) that re-examined a previous claim that light behind the knees could reset the circadian rhythm of an individual the same way as light to the eyes. One of three light treatments was randomly assigned to 22 subjects (a three-hour episode of bright lights to the eyes, to the knees, or to neither). Effects were measured two days later as the magnitude of phase shift in each subjects daily cycle of melatonin production, measured in hours. A negative measurement indicates a delay in melatonin production, which is the predicted effect of light treatment.

1. 1. Read the data from the file knees.csv

Exercise #3: One categorical and one continuous variable

The data are from L. Partridge and M. Farquhar (1981), Sexual activity and the lifespan of male fruit flies, Nature 294: 580-581. The experiment placed male fruit flies with varying numbers of previously-mated or virgin females to investigate whether mating activity affects male lifespan.

The linear model will have longevity as the response variable, and two explanatory variables: treatment (categorical) and thorax length (numerical; representing body size). The goal will be to compare differences in fly longevity among treatment groups, correcting for differences in thorax length. Correcting for thorax length will possibly improve the estimates of treatment effect. The method is also known as analysis of covariance, or ANCOVA.

1. 1. Read the data from the file fruitflies.csv
2. View the first few lines of data to make sure it was read correctly.
3. Determine whether the categorical variable treatment is a factor. If not a factor, convert treatment to a factor. This will be convenient when we fit the linear model.
4. Use the levels() command on the factor variable treatment to see how R has ordered the different treatment groups (should be alphabetically).
5. Change the order of the categories so that a sensible control group is first in the order of categories. Arrange the order of the remaining categories as you see fit.
6. Create a scatter plot, with longevity as the response variable and body size (thorax length) as the explanatory variable. Use a single plot with different symbols (and colors too, if you like) for different treatment groups. Or make a multipanel plot using the ggplot2 package
7. Fit a linear model to the fly data, including both body size (thorax length) and treatment as explanatory variables. Place thorax length before treatment in the model formula. Leave out the interaction term for now well assume for now that there is no interaction between the explanatory variables thorax and treatment.
8. Check whether the assumptions of linear models are met in this case. Are there any potential concerns? If you have done the analysis correctly, you will see that the variance of the residuals is not constant, but increases with increasing fitted values. This violates the linear model assumption of equal variance of residuals.
9. Attempt to fix the problem identified in step (2) using a log-transformation of the response variable. Refit the model and reapply the graphical diagnostic tools to check assumptions. Any improvements? (To my eye the situation is improved but the issue has not gone away entirely.) Lets continue anyway with the log-transformed analysis.
10. Visualize the fit of the model to the data using the visreg or ggeffects package. Try two different possibilities. In the first, plot the fit of the response variable to thorax length separately for each treatment group. In the second, plot the fit of the data to treatment, conditioning on the value of the covariate (thorax length).
11. Obtain 95% confidence intervals for the treatment and slope parameters. Obtain the parameter estimates and standard errors for the fitted model. Interpret the parameter estimates. What do they represent*? Which treatment group differs most from the control group?
12. Test overall treatment effects with an ANOVA table. Interpret each significance test what exactly is being tested?
13. Refit the model to the data but this time reverse the order in which you entered the two explanatory variables in the model. Test the treatment effects with an ANOVA table. Why isnt the table identical to the one from your analysis in 6?
14. Our analysis so far has assumed that the regression slopes for different treatment groups are the same. Is this a valid assumption? We have the opportunity to investigate just how different the estimated slopes really are. To do this, fit a new linear model to the data, but this time include an interaction term between the explanatory variables.
15. Another way to help assess whether the assumption of no interaction is a sensible one for these data is to determine whether the fit of the model is better when an interaction term is present or not, and by how much. We will learn new methods later in the course to determine this, but in the meantime a simple measure of model fit can be obtained using the adjusted R2 value. The ordinary R2 measures the fraction of the total variation in the response variable that is explained by the explanatory variables. This, however, cannot be compared between models that differ in the number of parameters because fitting more parameters always results in a larger R2, even if the added variables are just made-up random numbers. To compare the fit of models having different parameters, use the adjusted R2 value instead, which takes account of the number of parameters being fitted. Use the summary() command on each of two fitted models, one with and the other without an interaction term, and compare their adjusted R2 values. Are they much different? If not, then maybe it is OK to assume that any interaction term is likely small and can be left out.
